  <scaffolding>
    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Just-in-time quiz: What is a coprocessor?
- Secure Enclave: Dedicated, isolated security coprocessor in Apple's SoC (e.g., A-series chips). Physically separate from main CPU.
- Core functions: Stores cryptographic keys (symmetric/asymmetric), processes biometrics (Touch ID/Face ID templates never leave), aids secure boot.
- Key principle: Hardware isolation ensures keys/data never exposed to OS or apps, even if compromised.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Just-in-time quiz: How does Secure Enclave differ from software key stores?
- Isolation: Own memory, secure firmware; no shared bus with main processor.
- Relations: Similar to HSMs (tamper-resistant, FIPS-aligned) and TEEs (e.g., ARM TrustZone).
- Additional: Secure Intent (channel for main CPU to request ops), role in secure boot chain.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Just-in-time quiz: Name one API for key generation.
Step-by-step for developers:
1. Import Security.framework.
2. Generate key pair: SecKeyGeneratePair with kSecAttrTokenIDSecureEnclave.
3. Store/use: SecItemAdd to Keychain (backed by Enclave), perform ops via SecKeyCreateEncryptedData.
Example code:
```swift
let attributes: [String: Any] = [
    kSecAttrTokenID as String: kSecAttrTokenIDSecureEnclave,
    // ... other attrs
]
SecKeyGeneratePair(attributes as CFDictionary, &amp;publicKey, &amp;privateKey)
```
Best practices: Use biometric auth (LAContext), avoid key export.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Just-in-time quiz: How does Secure Enclave integrate with Keychain?
- With Keychain: Hardware-backed items (class kSecClassKey, tokenIDSecureEnclave).
- Secure Boot: Verifies boot chain integrity.
- App optimization: Combine with LocalAuthentication for biometrics; use for secure messaging (e.g., iMessage encryption).
- Advanced: Handle side-channels (timing/power analysis mitigations in firmware).</content>
    </layer>
